"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Revelation chapters 17–20
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-revelation-17-20.py

Key decisions in this range:
- Babylon (ch 17-18) as anti-type of the Bride (ch 21) — both "women" govern the Christological reading
- The rider on the white horse (19:11-16) is unambiguously Christ: Faithful and True (3:14), Word of God (John 1:1-14), KING OF KINGS
- The beast's parody of the divine formula ("was, is not, is to come") marks it as anti-Christ throughout
- The Lamb's book of life (20:15 → 21:27) links the final judgment to the slain Lamb identity
- "First resurrection" (20:5-6): interpreted as sharing in Christ's resurrection life (Rom 6; Col 2:12) governing the millennium debate
- The great white throne judgment (20:11-15): Christ is the judge (John 5:22, 27; Acts 17:31) — the Father has entrusted all judgment to the Son
- Death thrown into the lake of fire (20:14): fulfills 1 Cor 15:26 and 1:18 (Christ holds the keys of Death and Hades)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "17": {
    "1": '<p>The great prostitute sitting on many waters is introduced as the anti-type of the Bride (<em>nymphē</em>, 21:2, 9). Where the Bride is clothed in Christ\'s righteousness (19:8), the prostitute is clothed in imperial wealth and carries a cup of abominations. The structural parallelism forces a comparison: every human civilization offers itself as a bride to its inhabitants; only one Bride is legitimate.</p><p>The angel who shows John the prostitute (17:1) uses the same verb (<em>deiknymi</em>) as the angel who shows him the Bride (21:9) — the deliberate mirroring signals that the two visions interpret each other.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The kings of the earth who committed fornication with Babylon (17:2) are those who sought security, legitimacy, and economic benefit from the imperial cult system rather than from the Lamb. The contrast with 17:14 is stark: the kings who align with the beast go to war against the Lamb; the "called, chosen, and faithful" who are with the Lamb receive the opposite of what Babylon\'s clients receive.</p><p>The "wine of her immorality" echoes the prophetic condemnation of Babylon in Jer 51:7 — Babylon made the nations drink and go mad. Christ by contrast offers the wine of the new covenant (Mark 14:24; John 6:53-56) that does not intoxicate but gives life.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The beast with seven heads and ten horns that the woman rides is the same beast of 13:1 — the political power that derives its authority from the dragon (13:2), itself a parody of Christ who receives authority from the Father (Matt 28:18; John 5:27). The color scarlet (<em>kokkinos</em>) echoes the dragon\'s red color (12:3) and contrasts with the white linen of the Bride (19:8). The woman rides but does not control the beast — as 17:16 will show, the beast ultimately turns on her.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Purple and scarlet clothing, gold, jewels, and pearls (17:4) are the same luxury goods mourned in 18:12-16, and they deliberately contrast with the Bride\'s linen "bright and pure" (19:8). Where Babylon arrays herself in purchased wealth, the Bride is clothed in "righteous acts of the saints" — the gift of Christ\'s righteousness worked out in faithful suffering.</p><p>The golden cup full of abominations (<em>bdelygmatōn</em>) echoes Jesus\'s language for the desecrating sacrilege of Dan 9:27 (Matt 24:15) — Babylon\'s cup is a cup of judgment, the anti-type of the cup of the new covenant.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Mystery, Babylon the Great" written on her forehead mirrors the practice of Roman prostitutes who wore a placard with their name — the irony is that what Rome considers glory, God names as prostitution. The term "mystery" (<em>mystērion</em>) signals that this Babylon requires interpretation: it is not the historical Babylon destroyed in 539 BCE but the cipher for Rome, as Second Temple Jewish texts clearly show (4 Ezra 3:1-2; 1 Pet 5:13).</p><p>She is "the mother of prostitutes and of earth\'s abominations" — every city, empire, and power that demands ultimate loyalty from human beings participates in her spirit. The Christ-claim runs the opposite direction: "No one can serve two masters" (Matt 6:24).</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Drunk with the blood of the saints and the blood of the witnesses of Jesus" (17:6) answers the martyrs\' cry from beneath the altar in 6:9-11: "How long before you judge?" Babylon\'s guilt is precisely her murder of those whose testimony was Jesus. The phrase "witnesses of Jesus" (<em>martyrōn Iēsou</em>) connects directly to 1:2, 9; 12:17; 19:10 — to testify to Jesus is to share in the trajectory of the Lamb who was slain, and Babylon responds to that testimony with slaughter.</p><p>John\'s astonishment (<em>ethaumasen</em>) at the sight mirrors the astonishment of the earth-dwellers at the beast (13:3) — the reader is meant to feel the seductiveness of imperial power before the interpretation that follows strips away the glamour.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The angel\'s explanatory discourse (17:7-18) functions as apocalyptic interpretation of the vision — the same structure as Daniel 7-8 (vision followed by angelic interpretation). Christ is the key to reading apocalyptic: without the revelation given to the Lamb (5:5-7), the sealed scroll of history remains closed. The angel who interprets is acting under the Lamb\'s authority.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The beast "that was, and is not, and is to come" (17:8) is a direct parody of the divine formula "who is, and who was, and who is to come" (1:4, 8; 4:8). The substitution of "is to come" (<em>erchomenos</em>) with "goes to destruction" (<em>hypagei eis apōleian</em>) reveals the beast\'s ultimate trajectory. Christ comes to reign; the beast comes only to be destroyed. The "wonder" of the earth-dwellers whose names are not in the book of life contrasts with the worship of those whose names are written there (13:8; 21:27).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The seven hills identify Rome for any first-century reader. But the seven kings (17:10-11) reveal that the vision is less about topography than about the succession of imperial power and its ultimate subordination to the Lamb\'s sovereignty. All human empires — however many there are — operate within a numbered sequence under divine permission.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The fallen five kings and the "one who is" situate the vision in historical time while maintaining the seven-as-completeness symbolism characteristic of Revelation. The "short time" of the sixth king parallels the "short time" the devil knows he has (12:12) — a compressed urgency that frames the entire section. The Lamb has opened the scroll (5:5-7); the sequence of powers unfolds within his sovereign timing.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The beast that "was and is not, it is an eighth and belongs to the seven" (17:11) uses the symbolism of the ogdoad (eighth = beyond the week = new creation) but inverts it: the beast mimics resurrection and new-creation numbering. Christ is the genuine eighth — the first day of new creation, the resurrection day that stands beyond the Sabbath (John 20:1; 1 Cor 15:20). The beast\'s "eighth" is parody; Christ\'s is the substance.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The ten horns with authority "for one hour with the beast" are Parthian kings or, more broadly, all vassal powers who derive their authority from the beast-system. Their "one hour" authority contrasts with the Lamb\'s eternal kingdom (11:15; 22:5). The pattern of delegated but temporary authority under the beast maps against the pattern of delegated but eternal authority under Christ (Dan 7:13-14; Matt 28:18; 1 Cor 15:27-28).</p>',
    "13": '<p>The unanimous giving of power and authority to the beast (17:13) enacts the totalitarian claim of imperial power: it requires undivided loyalty. This is precisely the demand that the martyrs refused — they would not give their <em>exousia</em> to Caesar, which was what the imperial cult demanded in the oath of allegiance. The Lamb demands the same undivided loyalty (Matt 10:37-38; Luke 9:23) but offers it as gift rather than coercion.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"They will make war on the Lamb, and the Lamb will conquer them" (17:14) is the pivot of the entire Babylon vision. The mechanism of conquest is not military force but identity: he is "Lord of lords and King of kings" (the title that appears again at 19:16). Those with him are "called, chosen, and faithful" (<em>klētoi kai eklektoi kai pistoi</em>) — election language from the Synoptics (Matt 22:14; cf. John 6:37-39; Rom 8:28-30) combined with the faithfulness that is the mark of the Lamb himself (1:5; 3:14; 19:11).</p>',
    "15": '<p>"The waters where the prostitute sits are peoples and multitudes and nations and languages" (17:15) — the same fourfold formula used of those who worship the beast (13:7) and of those redeemed by the Lamb (5:9; 7:9). The prostitute and the Lamb both have universal reach; the difference is that the Lamb purchases by his blood while the prostitute purchases by offering economic security and political legitimacy.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The beast and the ten kings turning to devour the prostitute (17:16) shows that earthly political power is not a stable alliance. Babylon uses the beast but is ultimately consumed by it — "God has put it in their hearts to carry out his purpose" (17:17). This is the theological claim that is axiomatic throughout Revelation: even the enemies of God serve his purposes. The Lamb who opens the seals (6:1) remains sovereign even when evil turns on evil.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"For God has put it into their hearts to carry out his purpose" (17:17) — the Christological content here is that the Father\'s purpose centers on the Son\'s vindication. The whole sweep of imperial history, including the destruction of the whore by the beast, is moving toward "the words of God are fulfilled" — a phrase that elsewhere in Revelation specifically refers to the disclosure of what the Lamb has opened (10:7; 11:15).</p>',
    "18": '<p>The identification of the woman as "the great city that has dominion over the kings of the earth" (17:18) closes the interpretation. For John\'s readers this was transparently Rome. But the figure of Babylon-as-great-city recurs throughout prophetic literature (Isa 47; Jer 50-51; Ezek 26-28) and points to every human city that organizes itself around self-sufficient power rather than God\'s reign. The New Jerusalem (21:1-22:5) is the anti-type: the city whose builder and maker is God (Heb 11:10), whose light is the Lamb (21:23).</p>'
  },
  "18": {
    "1": '<p>The angel with great authority who illuminates the earth with his glory (18:1) is another of Revelation\'s luminous angelic figures who reflect the divine radiance. The announcement of Babylon\'s fall in the perfect tense — "Fallen, fallen is Babylon the Great" (18:2) — uses the prophetic perfect: the future is announced as already accomplished because the Lamb has already opened the scroll and the outcome is certain (5:5-7; 12:10-12). Christ\'s resurrection is the definitive event that guarantees every subsequent judgment.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Fallen, fallen is Babylon the great" repeats the angel\'s cry verbatim from 14:8, which was itself an echo of Isa 21:9 and Jer 51:8. The accumulation of allusions is deliberate: John is building a case that the prophetic word spoken against historical Babylon finds its ultimate fulfillment in the cosmic Babylon (Rome and its successors) now being judged. Christ as the Word of God (19:13; John 1:1) is the one in whom all prophetic words find their fulfillment (Luke 24:44; 2 Cor 1:20).</p>',
    "3": '<p>The kings who committed fornication with Babylon and the merchants who grew rich from her luxury trade (18:3) represent the two modes of relationship with imperial power: political legitimation and economic benefit. Both are offered as alternatives to dependence on the Lamb. The merchants\' grief at Babylon\'s fall (18:11-19) reveals that their real god was <em>ploutou</em> (wealth) — and wealth, as Jesus warned, is the primary competitor with the kingdom (Matt 6:24; 19:24; Luke 16:13).</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Come out of her, my people, lest you take part in her sins" (18:4) is a direct echo of Isa 52:11 ("Depart, depart, go out from there") and Jer 51:45 ("Come out of her, my people"), both in the context of Babylon judgment. The exodus typology is central: as Israel came out of Egypt through the blood of the Passover lamb, so the people of God are called out of the imperial system through the blood of the Lamb. The call is urgent because Babylon\'s sins "are heaped as high as heaven" — judgment is imminent.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"God has remembered her iniquities" (18:5) answers directly the prayer of the martyrs in 6:10 ("How long before you judge?"). In Hebrew theology, God\'s "remembering" (<em>zakar</em>) is not merely recollection but purposeful action — as he "remembered" Noah (Gen 8:1) and Hannah (1 Sam 1:19). The patience of 6:11 ("rest a little longer") is now exhausted. The Lamb who received the scroll has been executing judgment through the seals and trumpets; now the final judgment on the imperial system arrives.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Pay her back as she herself has paid back others, and repay her double for her deeds" (18:6) cites the principle of Jer 50:15, 29 ("as she has done, do to her") and the retribution law of the Mosaic covenant (Exod 21:24; Deut 19:19). The lex talionis is not vindictiveness but the restoration of justice: Babylon\'s double payment corresponds to her double guilt (against God and against his people). Christ as the righteous judge (2 Tim 4:8; Rev 19:11) executes this proportional judgment.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"She glorified herself and lived in luxury" (18:7) echoes the pride oracle against Tyre (Ezek 28:2-5) and the boast of historical Babylon (Isa 47:8-9). The specific phrase "I sit as a queen, I am no widow, and mourning I shall never see" directly quotes Isa 47:8 — Babylon\'s self-deification is her sin. The contrast is the Lamb who "emptied himself" (Phil 2:7) and the martyrs who did not love their lives unto death (12:11). Power through self-exaltation versus power through self-giving.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Her plagues will come in a single day" (18:8) echoes the one-day destruction of Sodom (Gen 19:24-25) and the sudden disaster oracles of Isa 47:9. The combination of pestilence, mourning, famine, and fire in a single day indicates divine judgment that operates outside ordinary historical causation. God "who judges her is mighty" (<em>ischyros Kyrios</em>, 18:8) — the title is God\'s alone (Exod 6:3; Ps 24:8; Isa 40:26) but in Revelation it belongs equally to Christ who is Almighty (1:8; 4:8; 11:17).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The kings\' lament "Alas, alas, you great city!" (18:10) echoes the dirges of Ezek 27 (for Tyre) and the prophetic laments for fallen cities throughout the Hebrew prophets. The weeping "from afar" because they fear her torment reveals the nature of their relationship: these were never allies in the deep sense, only clients who benefited from the system. The contrast with the New Jerusalem is stark — in the new city, the kings of the earth bring their glory in (21:24-26), having been purified of their complicity with Babylon.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"In a single hour your judgment has come" (18:10) repeats the "one hour" of 17:12 — the same compressed timeframe within which the beast\'s vassal-kings held their authority. God\'s judgment operates at a different timescale than human power projects: what takes generations to build can be undone in an hour. This is the theological counterpart to the Lamb\'s instant conquest of the beast in 19:20 — the decisive moment of judgment does not require drawn-out human warfare.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The merchants\' grief is explicitly self-interested: "since no one buys their cargo anymore" (18:11). The catalogue of luxury goods (18:12-13) ends with "slaves, that is, human souls" — the placement of persons at the end, as a commodity after cinnamon and wine, is a deliberate indictment. The contrast with Christ who purchased <em>anthrōpous</em> (human beings) by his blood (5:9) as free agents, not property, is total. Where Babylon commodifies the human person, Christ redeems it.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The cargo list beginning with gold, silver, jewels, and pearls (18:12) contrasts with the Bride whose adornment is the "glory of God" (21:11) and whose gates are pearls (21:21). Everything Babylon offers as luxury, the New Jerusalem provides as the city\'s permanent structure. The displacement of commercial categories by architectural ones signals that in the new creation, abundance is constitutive of the city rather than a trading relationship to be gained from an imperial center.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The cargo list ends with "slaves, that is, human souls" (<em>sōmata kai psychas anthrōpōn</em>, 18:13). The unusual addition of <em>psychas</em> (souls/lives) to the customary <em>sōmata</em> (bodies/slaves) appears to echo Ezek 27:13 but intensifies it: Babylon does not merely traffic in bodies but in the full personhood of human beings. This is the deepest anti-type of Christ\'s redemption, which purchases <em>psychas</em> by giving his own (Matt 20:28; Mark 10:45 — <em>lytrōsasthai</em> / <em>psychēn autou</em>).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"The fruit for which your soul longed has gone from you, and all your delicacies and your splendors are lost to you" (18:14) applies the desire-vocabulary (<em>epithumia tēs psychēs</em>) to Babylon\'s goods. The same vocabulary describes the desires that the world system feeds (1 John 2:16-17) and that Paul identifies as the works of the flesh (Gal 5:19-21). The Lamb offers the alternative: "those who hunger and thirst for righteousness will be satisfied" (Matt 5:6; John 6:35).</p>',
    "15": '<p>The merchants who stand "far off" (18:15) replicate the body language of Lev 13 (standing at a distance from the unclean) and of the disciples at the crucifixion (Luke 23:49 — standing at a distance). The fear of being implicated in judgment mirrors Peter\'s denial (John 18:25-27). The Christological irony is that those who refused to stand at a distance from Christ in his suffering (the women at the cross, Mary, John) are those who will stand near the Lamb in the new city.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Alas, alas, for the great city that was clothed in fine linen, in purple and scarlet, adorned with gold, with jewels, and with pearls" (18:16) inverts the clothing imagery systematically. The great city wears what the Bride will wear (19:8) but of a different quality: the prostitute\'s linen is purchased; the Bride\'s is given. The prostitute\'s jewels are accumulated by exploitation; the city\'s foundation stones are the apostles\' names (21:14) and the materials of pure divine gift (21:19-21).</p>',
    "17": '<p>"For in a single hour all this wealth has been laid waste" (18:17) — the ship captains\' lament echoes Ezek 27:29-36 (the mariners lamenting Tyre). The goods that constitute worldly wealth and power are subject to a single-hour reversibility that reveals their fundamental instability. The contrast with the "eternal weight of glory" (2 Cor 4:17) prepared for those who share Christ\'s suffering is explicit in Paul and implicit here: what Christ offers is irreversible because purchased by his own blood (Heb 9:12 — "eternal redemption").</p>',
    "18": '<p>"What city was like the great city?" (18:18) echoes the rhetorical questions of Ezek 27:32 and Tyre\'s lament. Rome\'s own propaganda celebrated Roma Aeterna — the eternal city. Here the eternal city is brought to ruin in an hour. The Christological reversal is that the city which crucified the Lord is not eternal; the city that "has no need of sun or moon to shine on it, for the glory of God gives it light, and its lamp is the Lamb" (21:23) is the only eternal city.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Dust cast on their heads (18:19) is the ancient grief gesture of Job 2:12 and Josh 7:6 — extremity of mourning. The irony is that the mourners are grieving for wealth, not for righteousness. The contrast with the heaven\'s rejoicing in the next verse (18:20) and the hallelujah chorus of 19:1-6 is stark: those whose treasure is in heaven (Matt 6:20) celebrate the fall of the system that persecuted them; those whose treasure was in Babylon mourn.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"Rejoice over her, O heaven, and you saints and apostles and prophets, for God has given judgment for you against her" (18:20) — the call to heaven to rejoice over judgment answers the martyrs\' prayer in 6:10. The witnesses (<em>martyres</em>) who gave their lives for the testimony of Jesus are vindicated: God has judged their case (<em>ekrinen ho theos to krima hymōn</em>). This is the courtroom language of Dan 7:22 — "judgment was given for the saints of the Most High." In Revelation, the Judge who delivers this verdict is the Lamb, enthroned at the Father\'s right hand (3:21; 5:6-7).</p>',
    "21": '<p>The millstone thrown into the sea (18:21) deliberately echoes Jesus\'s warning about causing "little ones" to stumble: "it would be better for him to have a great millstone fastened around his neck and to be drowned in the depth of the sea" (Matt 18:6; Mark 9:42). The allusion is not incidental — Babylon has done precisely what Jesus warned against, causing the "little ones who believe in me" to stumble through persecution and martyrdom. The millstone judgment is thus proportional to the millstone warning. The passage also cites Jer 51:63-64 (Seraiah casting a stone into the Euphrates).</p>',
    "22": '<p>"The sound of harpists and musicians, of flute players and trumpeters" will be heard no more in Babylon (18:22). The seven "no more" declarations (18:21-23) progressively strip away every dimension of cultural life — music, craft, work, light, marriage. The anti-creation character is total: these are the same elements that mark human civilization as God\'s gift (Gen 4:17-22). What the Lamb\'s new creation restores (21:23-26), Babylon\'s judgment removes permanently.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Your merchants were the great ones of the earth, and all nations were deceived by your sorcery" (18:23) identifies Babylon\'s fundamental sin as deception — the same charge Jesus makes against the devil (John 8:44: "a murderer from the beginning, a liar and the father of lies"). The great prostitute and the devil are aligned: both deceive the nations (20:3, 8) while the Lamb and his witnesses bear true testimony (1:2; 19:11; 22:6). The war between Babylon and the Lamb is at its deepest level a war between falsehood and truth.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"In her was found the blood of prophets and of saints, and of all who have been slain on earth" (18:24) makes Babylon responsible not just for the Roman persecutions but for all martyrdom from Abel onward — the same scope as Jesus\'s indictment of Jerusalem in Matt 23:35 ("from the blood of righteous Abel to the blood of Zechariah"). This universalization suggests that Rome is the representative and culmination of the anti-God power that has murdered witnesses throughout history. The vindication Christ won at the cross and resurrection has consequences that extend back to Abel.</p>'
  },
  "19": {
    "1": '<p>The great multitude\'s hallelujah (19:1) is the first of four occurrences in Revelation — all four in this chapter, and the only four in the NT. The word is a transliteration of the Hebrew <em>hallĕlû-yāh</em> (praise Yah/the LORD) from the Hallel psalms (Ps 113-118), sung at Passover. The heavenly chorus is celebrating the Passover of the new age — the salvation, glory, and power of God manifested in the judgment of Babylon and the vindication of the martyrs. Christ as the Passover Lamb (1 Cor 5:7; John 1:29; 19:36) is the reason the Hallel resounds in heaven.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"His judgments are true and just; for he has judged the great prostitute who corrupted the earth with her immorality, and has avenged on her the blood of his servants" (19:2) — the specific answer to the martyrs\' cry in 6:10. The divine attributes "true and just" (<em>alēthinai kai dikaiai</em>) applied to God\'s judgments are applied in 3:14 and 19:11 to Christ himself: "Faithful and True" (<em>pistos kai alēthinos</em>). The God who judges and the Christ who judges are identified by shared title.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"The smoke from her goes up forever and ever" (19:3) cites Isa 34:10 (the judgment of Edom: "its smoke shall go up forever"). The eternal smoke is not sadistic but typological: it is the sign that the judgment is final and unrepeatable, that the destruction of the anti-God system is permanent. This permanence is the necessary counterpart to the permanence of the new creation (21:4: "the former things have passed away") — both must be eternal for either to be meaningful.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The twenty-four elders and four living creatures falling down and worshiping (19:4) repeats the throne-room worship of chs 4-5. The connection is crucial: the worship that began at the Lamb\'s reception of the scroll (5:8-14) is now culminating in the fulfillment of that scroll\'s judgments. Every act of cosmic worship in Revelation has the Lamb at its center — here the Amen-hallelujah combines Hebrew liturgical acclamation with Greek transliteration to express that the worship is universal and definitive.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Praise our God, all you his servants, you who fear him, small and great" (19:5) echoes Ps 134:1 and 135:1 (Hallelujah psalms sung by the servants of the LORD). The inclusive "small and great" appears at the final judgment (20:12) and in the description of those who bear the beast\'s mark (13:16) — here it marks those who refused the mark and bore Christ\'s seal instead (7:3; 14:1). The servant-language is consistently applied to those who share Christ\'s cruciform pattern (Rom 1:1; Phil 2:7; Rev 1:1).</p>',
    "6": '<p>"For the Lord our God the Almighty reigns" (19:6) echoes Ps 97:1 and 99:1 ("The LORD reigns") — the royal enthronement psalms. The hallelujah chorus celebrates the definitive manifestation of God\'s kingship, which throughout Revelation runs through the Lamb\'s enthronement (5:6-7; 12:5, 10). The voice "like the roar of many waters and like the sound of mighty peals of thunder" echoes the voice of the Son of Man in 1:15 — the worship in heaven sounds like Christ himself.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Let us rejoice and exult and give him the glory, for the marriage of the Lamb has come, and his Bride has made herself ready" (19:7) — the marriage supper of the Lamb is the climax of the entire narrative arc. Jewish eschatological expectation included a great banquet at the end of the age (Isa 25:6-8; 2 Baruch 74:1; 1 Enoch 62:14), and Jesus himself used the marriage feast as a primary image for the kingdom (Matt 22:1-14; 25:1-13; John 3:29). The Lamb is both the slain sacrifice and the bridegroom — both identities are held simultaneously.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"It was granted her to clothe herself with fine linen, bright and pure — for the fine linen is the righteous deeds of the saints" (19:8) — the passive "it was granted" (<em>edothē</em>) signals divine gift. The Bride\'s righteous deeds are not self-generated but given: the same pattern as Eph 2:10 ("we are his workmanship, created in Christ Jesus for good works, which God prepared beforehand"). The white linen contrasts with Babylon\'s purple and scarlet: one is given, one is purchased. The garment that came from washing in the Lamb\'s blood (7:14) is here described from the inside as the saints\' faithful acts.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Blessed are those who are invited to the marriage supper of the Lamb" (19:9) is the fourth of Revelation\'s seven beatitudes (1:3; 14:13; 16:15; 19:9; 20:6; 22:7, 14). The invitation to the marriage supper echoes the parable of Matt 22:1-14 where those first invited refuse and the servants go out to invite others. Here the invitation is to all who have washed their robes in the Lamb\'s blood (7:14). The angel\'s "These are the true words of God" (19:9) carries an implicit Christological claim: Jesus himself is "the Amen, the faithful and true witness" (3:14; cf. John 14:6).</p>',
    "10": '<p>John\'s prostration before the angel and the angel\'s refusal ("Worship God!") establish the principle that no mediating figure — not the greatest angel, not the most glorious vision — may receive the worship due God alone. The crucial addition: "For the testimony of Jesus is the spirit of prophecy" (<em>hē gar martyria Iēsou estin to pneuma tēs prophēteias</em>). All prophetic speech that bears the Spirit\'s authority has Jesus as its testimony, its referent, and its content. This is the most compact Christological hermeneutic in Revelation: prophecy\'s purpose is to witness to Jesus.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Then I saw heaven opened, and behold, a white horse! The one sitting on it is called Faithful and True (<em>Pistos kai Alēthinos</em>)" (19:11) — the parousia vision. The two-part name recalls 3:14 ("the faithful and true witness") and 6:10 ("sovereign Lord, holy and true"). The rider "judges and makes war in righteousness" — not for vengeance but for the restoration of right order. The white horse parallels the first seal rider (6:2), but where that rider was ambiguous, this rider is unambiguous: his names identify him beyond doubt.</p>',
    "12": '<p>His eyes "like a flame of fire" (19:12) repeat the description from 1:14 and 2:18, where the same description introduces the Son of Man\'s penetrating judgment. "On his head are many diadems" (<em>polloi diadēmata</em>) — where the beast wore seven (13:1) and the dragon ten (12:3), the rider wears many, indicating surpassing and unlimited sovereignty. The "name written that no one knows but himself" points to the divine ineffability (cf. Exod 3:14; the unspeakable divine name in Jewish tradition) while marking the rider as the divine Son.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"He is clothed in a robe dipped in blood, and the name by which he is called is The Word of God" (19:13). The blood-stained robe cites Isa 63:1-6 (the divine warrior returning from judgment with garments stained from the winepress), but the paradox is that the blood on his robe is his own — the Lamb comes already marked by his own slaughter (5:6). The title "Word of God" (<em>ho Logos tou Theou</em>) identifies the rider unmistakably with the Logos of John 1:1-14: the one through whom all things were made is the same one who comes in judgment and redemption.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The armies of heaven "arrayed in fine linen, white and pure" (19:14) are clothed identically to the Bride (19:8) — they are the same people, the saints, now participating in the Lamb\'s victory. Their white-and-pure linen marks them as those who have washed their robes (7:14) and whose righteous deeds were granted to them (19:8). The rider goes before them, not they before him: this is not a human military campaign but a divine conquest in which the saints participate as witnesses.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The sharp sword from his mouth (19:15) is the sword of 1:16 and 2:12 — Christ\'s word as the instrument of judgment (Isa 49:2; 2 Thess 2:8; Heb 4:12). The iron rod echoes Ps 2:9 (the Son\'s rule over the nations), cited also at 2:27 and 12:5. The winepress of "the fury of the wrath of God the Almighty" (19:15) combines the Isa 63:3 imagery with the cup of judgment (14:19-20) — the same cup that Jesus asked the Father to take from him in Gethsemane (Matt 26:39), which he nevertheless drank on behalf of those who receive the marriage supper invitation.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The invitation to the "great supper of God" (19:17) is the anti-feast that parallels the marriage supper of the Lamb (19:9). The contrast is explicit and deliberate: in 19:9 the blessed are invited; in 19:17 the birds are invited to eat the flesh of kings, generals, and the mighty. The passage draws on Ezek 39:17-20 (God\'s invitation to the birds after Gog\'s defeat) — the anti-Gog battle that follows in 20:8-9 makes the connection explicit. The two suppers represent the two ultimate destinies structured around one\'s relationship to the Lamb.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The list of those consumed at the great supper of God — "kings, generals, mighty men, horses, riders, free, slave, small, great" (19:18) — mirrors the list of those who hid from the Lamb\'s wrath in 6:15 and the list of those who bore the beast\'s mark (13:16). Social hierarchy provides no protection at the Lamb\'s judgment: those who used their status to persecute the saints find their status irrelevant before the one to whom "all authority in heaven and on earth has been given" (Matt 28:18).</p>',
    "19": '<p>The beast and the kings of the earth gathered "to make war against him who was sitting on the horse and against his army" (19:19) — this is the culmination of the anti-Lamb coalition that was assembled at Armageddon (16:14-16). The war that "the whole world" has been preparing is now joined, but the outcome is determined before it begins: the Lamb has already overcome in 5:5 and 12:11. The gathering itself is within the sovereign permission of God (16:14: God sends the foul spirits to gather them).</p>',
    "20": '<p>The beast and the false prophet are captured and "thrown alive into the lake of fire that burns with sulfur" (19:20). The lake of fire first appears here — before Death and Hades receive it (20:14) and before any human beings are cast in (20:15). The beast\'s fate precedes everyone else\'s: the system of empire and the system of propaganda that enforced the imperial cult both receive judgment before the final judgment of the dead. The Lamb\'s victory over the beast is the prelude to his victory over Death itself (20:14; 1 Cor 15:26).</p>',
    "21": '<p>"The rest were killed by the sword that came from the mouth of him who was sitting on the horse" (19:21) — the sword of the Word (Heb 4:12; Isa 49:2; 2 Thess 2:8). The passive "were killed" without any angelic or human instrument other than the Word underscores that the rider\'s conquest is entirely by the power of divine speech. This is the Christological claim: the same Word by which the world was created (John 1:3) is the Word by which it is judged and renewed. The birds were "gorged with their flesh" — the anti-feast is complete.</p>'
  },
  "20": {
    "1": '<p>The angel descending from heaven with the key to the bottomless pit (20:1) operates under Christ\'s authority — Christ himself "has the keys of Death and Hades" (1:18). The binding of Satan for a thousand years enacts what Christ announced in advance: "I saw Satan fall like lightning from heaven" (Luke 10:18) and "Now will the ruler of this world be cast out" (John 12:31). The Christus Victor theology that runs throughout Revelation reaches a penultimate expression here: the devil\'s power is bound precisely because Christ has conquered him through death and resurrection.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Satan is identified with four names in 20:2: the dragon (12:3-4), the ancient serpent (Gen 3:1-15), the devil (Greek: slanderer), and Satan (Hebrew: adversary). All four names appear together in 12:9 at his expulsion from heaven. The thousand-year binding is read against the background of 1 Enoch 10:4-6 (Azazel/Semyaza bound in preparation for final judgment), Jude 6, and 2 Pet 2:4 — a Second Temple tradition that Christ\'s work now enacts definitively for the chief adversary.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Satan is sealed in the pit "so that he might not deceive the nations any longer" (20:3). His primary activity throughout Revelation is deception — 12:9 names it explicitly: "the deceiver of the whole world." Christ by contrast is "Faithful and True" (19:11) and the "faithful and true witness" (3:14). The millennium is the period in which the nations are freed from Satan\'s wholesale deception — the mission of the church to all nations (Matt 28:19-20) takes place within this window of bound deception. The "must be released" (20:3) is God\'s sovereign permission for the final testing.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"They came to life and reigned with Christ for a thousand years" (20:4) — the "first resurrection" that grants the saints co-reign with Christ. The pattern follows Pauline language: those who have died with Christ are raised with Christ (Rom 6:3-5; Col 2:12; 2 Tim 2:11-12 "if we have died with him, we will also live with him; if we endure, we will also reign with him"). Those specifically in view are those who were beheaded for their testimony (<em>martyria</em>) of Jesus — the martyr-witnesses whose cause was vindicated in ch 18-19. They now share Christ\'s enthronement (3:21; Eph 2:6).</p>',
    "5": '<p>"The rest of the dead did not come to life until the thousand years were ended. This is the first resurrection" (20:5). The "first resurrection" is distinguished from the resurrection of the rest of the dead (20:12-13), suggesting two resurrections — a reading that goes back to 1 Cor 15:20-24 ("Christ the firstfruits, then at his coming those who belong to Christ, then comes the end"). Christ himself is the first resurrection (John 11:25: "I am the resurrection and the life"), and those who share in him share in his resurrection-life now (John 5:24-25; Col 3:1).</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Blessed and holy is the one who shares in the first resurrection" (20:6) is the fifth beatitude (cf. 1:3; 14:13; 16:15; 19:9; 22:7, 14). Those who share in it are priests of God and of Christ — the royal priesthood of 1 Pet 2:9, Exod 19:6, and Rev 1:6. "Over such the second death has no power" — because those who have died with Christ in baptism (Rom 6:3-4) and through martyrdom are already on the resurrection side of death. The second death (20:14: the lake of fire) has no jurisdiction over those who have already passed through death into Christ\'s life.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Satan\'s release after the thousand years (20:7) is not an escape but a sovereign permission ("must be released," 20:3) — the "little while" of his second freedom corresponds to the "little while" of his earlier fury after expulsion from heaven (12:12). The deliberate echo signals that the final deception follows the same pattern as the persecution of the saints: intensified pressure followed by definitive defeat. God permits the final deception precisely to expose every remaining opposition and to complete the separation.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Gog and Magog (20:8) — the eschatological cipher drawn from Ezek 38-39, where Gog of the land of Magog leads a coalition against restored Israel. By John\'s time the Gog-Magog tradition had become a flexible symbol for the final, comprehensive attack of the nations on God\'s people (Qumran War Scroll 1QM; b. Sanhedrin 97b; m. Eduyot 2:10). The "four corners of the earth" expresses geographic totality — this is a universal final assault, not a regional conflict. The contrast with the Lamb\'s gathering of nations to new Jerusalem (21:24-26) could not be sharper.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Fire came down from heaven and consumed them" (20:9) — divine fire without any instrument or human army. The echo is of Elijah\'s fire from heaven (1 Kgs 18:38; 2 Kgs 1:10-12) and the Sodom judgment (Gen 19:24), but more immediately of Ezek 38:22 and 39:6 (fire and sulfur on Gog). The "beloved city" (20:9) echoes Ps 78:68 and 87:2 (Jerusalem as beloved) but in context refers to the camp of the saints — the messianic community that is the locus of God\'s presence. The fire comes down from heaven because Christ is enthroned in heaven (1:13-16; 3:21) and the judgment flows from his throne.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The devil thrown into the lake of fire (20:10) — the same destiny as the beast and false prophet (19:20), now joined by their instigator. "Tormented day and night forever and ever" uses the same formula as the smoke of Babylon (19:3) and the smoke of those who take the beast\'s mark (14:11). The finality is the point: this is not an intermediate state but the permanent destination of the adversary, whose career of deception is permanently ended. The Christological significance is that Christ\'s victory at the cross over the "ruler of this world" (John 12:31; Col 2:15) is here finally, visibly consummated.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The great white throne (20:11) from which "earth and sky fled away" echoes Dan 7:9-10 (the Ancient of Days enthroned) and 1 Enoch 47:3. The fleeing of earth and heaven is the dissolution of the present cosmos in preparation for the new creation (21:1). The judge seated on the throne is identified implicitly with Christ throughout Revelation — the Father has entrusted all judgment to the Son (John 5:22, 27; Acts 17:31; Rom 2:16; 2 Cor 5:10; 2 Tim 4:1). The white throne is the Lamb\'s throne (22:1, 3: "the throne of God and of the Lamb").</p>',
    "12": '<p>The dead "small and great" standing before the throne (20:12) echoes the social catalogue of those who bore the beast\'s mark (13:16) — no status or position grants exemption from this judgment. Two sets of books are opened: the books of deeds, and the book of life. The book of life is the Lamb\'s book (21:27: "the book of life of the Lamb who was slain") — those written in it are those purchased by the Lamb\'s blood (5:9). The two books represent two bases of judgment: works and grace, held simultaneously in the Lamb\'s judicial act.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"The sea gave up the dead who were in it, Death and Hades gave up the dead who were in them" (20:13) — the universal scope of resurrection. No mode of death, no location of burial, puts a human being beyond the reach of the Lamb who "has the keys of Death and Hades" (1:18). The sea in apocalyptic represents chaos and unreachable depth (Job 38:16-17; Ps 139:8-10); even the sea\'s dead are recoverable. This is the cosmic fulfillment of Jesus\'s promise: "All that the Father gives me will come to me" (John 6:37) and "I will raise it up on the last day" (John 6:39-40).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Then Death and Hades were thrown into the lake of fire. This is the second death, the lake of fire" (20:14). The death of Death fulfills 1 Cor 15:26 ("the last enemy to be destroyed is death") and Isa 25:8 ("he will swallow up death forever"). Christ who "holds the keys of Death and Hades" (1:18) now permanently locks those powers in the lake of fire. Hosea 13:14 (cited in 1 Cor 15:55-56: "O death, where is your victory?") is the prophetic basis: the Christ-event that Paul celebrates as accomplished proleptically in the resurrection is here shown as consummated cosmically. Death is not merely overcome but destroyed.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"If anyone\'s name was not found written in the book of life, he was thrown into the lake of fire" (20:15) — the book of life is the Lamb\'s book (21:27), written before the foundation of the world (13:8; 17:8; cf. Luke 10:20; Phil 4:3; Heb 12:23). The judgment is therefore not arbitrary but follows from each person\'s relationship to the Lamb whose blood purchased those in the book (5:9). The second death has no power over those in the first resurrection (20:6), who are those in the Lamb\'s book — the two descriptions are coextensive. The lake of fire is the permanent separation from the Lamb\'s presence that those who rejected him chose (2 Thess 1:9).</p>'
  }
}

